1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
We are in Pęgów.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:09,000
It is quite an unusual
name for a village.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000
But even more interesting is
that in 1947

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:19,000
this place was called Henryków.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:24,000
It was a Polish version
of the German name

6
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Henigsdorf.

7
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It meant
“Hennig’s village”.

8
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Why was the name changed?
And how was it decided?

9
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:44,000
The second answer is simple.

10
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,000
South of Wrocław,
there is another Henryków.

11
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Two places with the same name
caused confusion.

12
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
So a change was needed.

13
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
But how did Henryków
become Pęgów?

14
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Officials checked
old 13th-century records.

15
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
They found a village name:
Panglouo.

16
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Old notes described
a border stone.

17
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
It was between Machnice,
Brochocin and Pęgów.

18
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
The first two villages
still exist today.

19
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:34,000
They are quite close by.

20
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
But are they close enough
for a border stone?

21
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
What do you think?

22
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
Are we in ancient Panglouo,

23
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
or in “Hennig’s village”?